    <text>
        <body>
      
		<pb n="1"/>
			<p><addressee>Mr Leeser</addressee>&#44;</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir&#44;</p>
          <p rend="indent(2)">I send you a<lb/> Circular of a school in which<lb/> I am hereafter to be engaged&#44; and<lb/> take the liberty of asking your<lb/> influence in my behalf. In doing<lb/> so&#44; I feel perfectly assured we<lb/> shall merit your confidence.<lb/> On entering this school&#44; I am<lb/> altogether satisfied with the<lb/> operations of this Institution&#44;<lb/> the system being the same<lb/> as that of the Troy Seminary&#44;<lb/> and <persName>Mrs. Phelps</persName>&#39; of <placeName>Maryland</placeName>.<lb/> The teachers in every depart&#45;</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p>&#45;ment&#44; are there of <add>&#63;</add>&#44;<lb/> experience and faithfulness&#59;&#8212;<lb/> the advantages enjoyed in<lb/> <add>&#63;</add>&#44; are hardly second to<lb/> a <add>&#63;</add> school. Excuse the<lb/> liberty I have taken&#44; and<lb/> believe me&#44; I should not<lb/> have <add>&#63;</add>entured&#44; had I not<lb/> been fully aware of your<lb/> kind and benevolent<lb/> character.</p>
          <p rend="indent(8)">Truly yours</p>
          <p rend="indent(9)"><persName role="author">E. C. Barton</persName>.</p>
			<p><date>June 19<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1852</date></p>
          <p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>254 Walnut St.</placeName></p>
          
        </body>
